[[Major general|Major General]] '''Lancelot Daryl Hickes''' [[Order of the Bath|CB]] [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] [[Military Cross|MC]] (1884-1965) was a senior [[British Army]] officer during the [[World War II|Second World War]].

==Biography==

Born on 30 May 1884, Lancelot Hickes was educated at [[Bedford School]] and at the [[Royal Military Academy, Woolwich]]. He received his first commission as a [[Second lieutenant|Second Lieutenant]] in the [[Royal Artillery]] in 1903. He served during the [[World War I|First World War]] and was [[mentioned in dispatches]] four times, receiving the [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] and the [[Military Cross]]. Promoted to the rank of [[Major general|Major General]] in 1938, he was [[General officer commanding|General Officer Commanding]], 3rd Anti-Aircraft Division, between 1938 and 1939. He served during the [[World War II|Second World War]] and was Director of Staff Duties at the [[War Office]] between 1939 and 1941.<ref>[http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whowaswho/U51839/HICKES_Maj.-Gen._Lancelot_Daryl?index=1&results=QuicksearchResults&query=0 Who's Who<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

[[Major general|Major General]] Lancelot Hickes became an [[Order of the British Empire|Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] in 1919,<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/31370/page/6800/data.pdf</ref> and a [[Order of the Bath|Commander of the Order of the Bath]] in 1941.<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/35029/supplement/3/data.pdf</ref> He retired from the [[British Army]] in 1942 and died on 4 October 1965.

